  "response": "Here are some recommended books for learning math systematically:\n\n1. Foundational/Basic Mathematics\n- \"Basic Mathematics\" by Serge Lang\n- \"How to Solve It\" by George P\u00f3lya (problem-solving strategies)\n\n2. Algebra\n- \"Algebra\" by Michael Artin\n- \"Abstract Algebra\" by David S. Dummit and Richard M. Foote\n\n3. Calculus\n- \"Calculus\" by James Stewart\n- \"Calculus: Early Transcendentals\" by James Stewart\n- \"Calculus Made Easy\" by Silvanus P. Thompson\n\n4. Linear Algebra\n- \"Linear Algebra and Its Applications\" by Gilbert Strang\n- \"Introduction to Linear Algebra\" by Gilbert Strang\n\n5. Discrete Mathematics\n- \"Discrete Mathematics and Its Applications\" by Kenneth Rosen\n\n6. Advanced/Comprehensive\n- \"What Is Mathematics?\" by Richard Courant and Herbert Robbins\n- \"The Cartoon Guide to Mathematics\" by Larry Gonick\n\n7. Online Resources\n- Khan Academy (free online courses)\n- MIT OpenCourseWare\n\nStart with foundational books and progress gradually. Your learning pace and background will determine which resources work best for you.",
